Q. So if it the case 1 of the continuation of the Theory Example 24 , then what happens and why?

Ans: 🔷 Case 1 Recap

     import java.io.IOException;

     class MyException extends IOException {}

     class Parent {
         void read() throws IOException {
             System.out.println("Parent read");
         }
     }

     class Child extends Parent {
         @Override
         void read() throws MyException {
             System.out.println("Child read");
             throw new MyException();
         }
     }

     🔷 What happens here?
     ✅ 1️⃣ Compilation

     ✔ Compiles successfully

     👉 Because:
     -MyException is a subclass of IOException
     -So it follows the rule

     🔷 2️⃣ Runtime behavior (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

     Parent obj = new Child();
     obj.read();

     🔍 Step-by-step

     👉 Step 1: Reference type

     Parent obj

     Compiler thinks:

     “This method may throw IOException”

     👉 Step 2: Object type

     new Child()

     At runtime:

     Child’s method runs (method overriding)

     👉 Step 3: Method execution

     Child read() → throws MyException

     👉 So actual exception thrown:

     MyException

     🔷 3️⃣ Exception Handling

     You must handle it like this:

     try {
         obj.read();
     } catch (IOException e) {
         System.out.println("Handled");
     }

     🧠 Why catch IOException works?

     👉 Because:

     MyException IS-A IOException

     👉 So parent type can catch child exception

     🔷 🔥 Important Concept

     👉 Compile-time vs Runtime

     Stage	                                         What happens

     Compile-time	                                 Sees IOException
     Runtime	                                     Throws MyException

     🔷 Output

     Child read
     Handled

     🔷 🔥 Key Insight (VERY IMPORTANT)

     👉 Even though child throws MyException:

     ✔ Caller only needs to handle parent exception (IOException)

     🔷 Why Java allows this?

     👉 Because of polymorphism

     If this was NOT allowed:

     Parent obj = new Child();

     👉 Would break consistency

     🔷 Real-life analogy

     Parent says:

     “I may throw a file error”

     Child says:

     “I throw a specific file error”

     👉 Caller:

     “Okay, I’ll handle file errors”

     ✔ Works perfectly

     🔷 🔥 Interview Answer
     👉
     If the child class throws a subclass of the parent’s exception, the code compiles
     successfully. At runtime, the child’s method is executed and the subclass exception is
     thrown, but it can still be handled using the parent exception type due to polymorphism.

     🔷 One-line memory trick
     👉
     Compile-time sees parent exception, runtime throws child exception

     Reason:

     So in the try-catch one we are throwing IO Exception , as we reference type is Parent
     so what are the types accessible for Exception handling it is IO Exception only , as the
     handling capability depends on the ref type. Also by the rule of the exception , we know
     that the child can't throw broader exception, so the parent type of exception is the
     broader one then the child type will def be able to handle it.
     So this passes the compile time .

     (so at compile time it sees the parent type and the Child IS-A parent type so it expects a
     IO exception only , and during runtime due to broader type of exception of the parent-child
     rule it passes obviously.)

     The actual thing that happens in runtime is:
     Due to overriding the child methods will be called actually , so what actually runs at runtime
     depends on the actual object created , and we have the actual obj of Child class.
     So all the child classes method will be executed , along with it's exception will be thrown
     which would def be handled by the try-catch block .